tical anxiety concerning how to limit their potential effects. In light of Locke's views on education, Mehta concludes that the promise of liberation at the heart of liberalism is vitiated by its constraints on cognitive and political freedom.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 4aPhilosophy. 4aPolitical Science & Political History. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / History & Theory.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Archive Pre-2000z978311053617140uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/9781501726392?locatt=mode:legacyzOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501726392zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501726392/original  a978-3-11-053617-1 Cornell University Press Archive Pre-2000b2000  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA